{"title_page": "Mark Mattson", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Mark Mattson\n| image             = Mark Mattson.JPG\n| image_size        = 200px\n| caption           = Mark Mattson in 2009.\n| birth_name        = Mark P. Mattson\n| birth_date        = 1957\n| birth_place       = Rochester, Minnesota\n| nationality       = American\n| fields =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Neuroscience]]\n* [[Aging]]\n  }}\n| workplaces =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[National Institute on Aging]]\n* [[Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine]]\n  }}\n| alma_mater =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Iowa State University]]\n* [[North Texas State University]]\n* [[University of Iowa]]\n* [[Colorado State University]]\n  }}\n| spouse =\n  {{plainlist |\n* Joanne Mattson\n}}\n}}\n'''Mark P. Mattson''' is a Professor of Neuroscience at [[Johns Hopkins University]].<ref name=faculty>[https://neuroscience.jhu.edu/research/faculty/57 Mark P. Mattson]. Johns Hopkins School of Medicine.</ref> He is the former Chief of the Laboratory of Neurosciences at the National Institute on Aging Intramural Research Program of the [[National Institute on Aging]].<ref name=intsymp>{{cite web|title=International Symposium to Honor Pioneer in Neuroscience and Fasting|url=https://www.nia.nih.gov/news/international-symposium-honor-pioneer-neuroscience-and-fasting|website=National Institute on Aging|date=May 29, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|quote=one of the world\u2019s top experts on the potential cognitive and physical health benefits of intermittent fasting}}</ref>\n\nMattson has done research on [[intermittent fasting]].<ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg24032000-200-fasting-power-can-going-without-food-really-make-you-healthier/ \"Fasting power: Can going without food really make you healthier?\"]. ''New Scientist''.</ref> The National Institute of Health considers him \"one of the world\u2019s top experts on the potential cognitive and physical health benefits of intermittent fasting\".<ref name=intsymp/>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nMattson was elected a Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] for research revealing the cellular mechanisms involved in neural plasticity \u2014 the ability of neurons to adapt during processes like learning or injury \u2014 and development of neurodegenerative disorders. He is the recipient of the [[Alzheimer's Association]] Zenith Award, the Metropolitan Life Foundation Medical Research Award, and the Santiago Grisolia Chair Prize.  He was as the founding Editor and Editor-in-Chief of NeuroMolecular Medicine and [[Ageing Research Reviews]].<ref name=intsymp/>\n\nOn June 3, 2019, an International Symposium, \"Pathways Towards and Away from Brain Health,\" was held to honor him on his retirement from the NIH.<ref name=intsymp />\n\n== Selected publications ==\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Furukawa K, Barger SW, Blalock E, Mattson MP E|title=Activation of K+ channels and suppression of neuronal activity by secreted \uf062-amyloid precursor protein | journal=Nature | volume=379 | pages=74-8 | date=1996 | pmid=8538744}}\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Mattson MP E|title=Pathways towards and away from Alzheimer\u2019s disease | journal=Nature | volume=430 | issue=7000 | pages=631-9 | date=August 2004 | pmid=15295589 | doi=10.1038/nature02621}}\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Stranahan AM, Mattson MP E|title=Recruiting adaptive cellular stress responses for successful brain aging | journal=Nature Rev Neurosci  | volume=13 | issue=3 | pages=209-16 | date=2012 | pmid=22251954}}\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Cheng A, Yang Y, Zhou Y, Maharana C, Lu D, Peng W, Liu Y, Wan R, Marosi K, Misiak M, Bohr VA, Mattson MP E|title=Mitochondrial SIRT3 mediates adaptive responses of neurons to exercise, and metabolic and excitatory challenges | journal=Cell Metab | volume=23 | issue=1 | pages=128-42 | date=January 2016  | pmid=26698917}}\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Mattson MP, Moehl K, Ghena N, Schmaedick M, Cheng A E|title=Intermittent metabolic switching, neuroplasticity and brain health | journal=Nat Rev Neurosci | volume=19 | issue=26 | pages=63-80 | date=February 2018 | pmid=22251954}}\u2003\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Mattson MP, de Cabo R E|title=Effects of intermittent fasting on health, aging, and disease | journal=New Engl J Med | volume=381 | issue=26 | pages=2541-51 | date=December 26, 2019 | pmid=31881139 | doi=10.1056/NEJMra1905136}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://neuroscience.jhu.edu/research/faculty/57/MarkMattson.php Johns Hopkins profile of Mark Mattson]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mattson, Mark}}\n\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Colorado State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Fasting researchers]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Mark Mattson\n| image             = Mark Mattson.JPG\n| image_size        = 200px\n| caption           = Mark Mattson in 2009.\n| birth_name        = Mark P. Mattson\n| birth_date        = 1957\n| birth_place       = Rochester, Minnesota\n| nationality       = American\n| fields =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Neuroscience]]\n* [[Aging]]\n  }}\n| workplaces =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[National Institute on Aging]]\n* [[Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine]]\n  }}\n| alma_mater =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Iowa State University]]\n* [[North Texas State University]]\n* [[University of Iowa]]\n* [[Colorado State University]]\n  }}\n| spouse =\n  {{plainlist |\n* Joanne Mattson\n}}\n}}\n'''Mark P. Mattson''' is a Professor of Neuroscience at [[Johns Hopkins University]].<ref name=faculty>[https://neuroscience.jhu.edu/research/faculty/57 Mark P. Mattson]. Johns Hopkins School of Medicine.</ref> He is the former Chief of the Laboratory of Neurosciences at the National Institute on Aging Intramural Research Program of the [[National Institute on Aging]].<ref name=intsymp>{{cite web|title=International Symposium to Honor Pioneer in Neuroscience and Fasting|url=https://www.nia.nih.gov/news/international-symposium-honor-pioneer-neuroscience-and-fasting|website=National Institute on Aging|date=May 29, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|quote=one of the world\u2019s top experts on the potential cognitive and physical health benefits of intermittent fasting}}</ref>\n\nMattson has done research on [[intermittent fasting]].<ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg24032000-200-fasting-power-can-going-without-food-really-make-you-healthier/ \"Fasting power: Can going without food really make you healthier?\"]. ''New Scientist''.</ref> The National Institute of Health considers him \"one of the world\u2019s top experts on the potential cognitive and physical health benefits of intermittent fasting\".<ref name=intsymp/>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nMattson was elected a Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] for research revealing the cellular mechanisms involved in neural plasticity \u2014 the ability of neurons to adapt during processes like learning or injury \u2014 and development of neurodegenerative disorders. He is the recipient of the [[Alzheimer's Association]] Zenith Award, the Metropolitan Life Foundation Medical Research Award, and the Santiago Grisolia Chair Prize.  He was as the founding Editor and Editor-in-Chief of NeuroMolecular Medicine and [[Ageing Research Reviews]].<ref name=intsymp/>\n\nOn June 3, 2019, an International Symposium, \"Pathways Towards and Away from Brain Health,\" was held to honor him on his retirement from the NIH.<ref name=intsymp />\n\n== Selected publications ==\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Furukawa K, Barger SW, Blalock E, Mattson MP E|title=Activation of K+ channels and suppression of neuronal activity by secreted \uf062-amyloid precursor protein | journal=Nature | volume=379 | pages=74-8 | date=1996 | pmid=8538744}}\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Mattson MP E|title=Pathways towards and away from Alzheimer\u2019s disease | journal=Nature | volume=430 | issue=7000 | pages=631-9 | date=August 2004 | pmid=15295589 | doi=10.1038/nature02621}}\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Stranahan AM, Mattson MP E|title=Recruiting adaptive cellular stress responses for successful brain aging | journal=Nature Rev Neurosci  | volume=13 | issue=3 | pages=209-16 | date=2012 | pmid=22251954}}\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Cheng A, Yang Y, Zhou Y, Maharana C, Lu D, Peng W, Liu Y, Wan R, Marosi K, Misiak M, Bohr VA, Mattson MP E|title=Mitochondrial SIRT3 mediates adaptive responses of neurons to exercise, and metabolic and excitatory challenges | journal=Cell Metab | volume=23 | issue=1 | pages=128-42 | date=January 2016  | pmid=26698917}}\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Mattson MP, Moehl K, Ghena N, Schmaedick M, Cheng A E|title=Intermittent metabolic switching, neuroplasticity and brain health | journal=Nat Rev Neurosci | volume=19 | issue=26 | pages=63-80 | date=February 2018 | pmid=22251954}}\u2003\n*{{cite journal | vauthors=Mattson MP, de Cabo R E|title=Effects of intermittent fasting on health, aging, and disease | journal=New England Journal of Medicine | volume=381 | issue=26 | pages=2541-51 | date=December 26, 2019 | pmid=31881139 | doi=10.1056/NEJMra1905136}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://neuroscience.jhu.edu/research/faculty/57/MarkMattson.php Johns Hopkins profile of Mark Mattson]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mattson, Mark}}\n\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Colorado State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Fasting researchers]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa alumni]]\n", "name_user": "LogicandProportion", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected publications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Mattson"}
{"title_page": "George Essex Evans", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> \n| name         = George Essex Evans\n| image        = GeorgeEssexEvans.jpg\n| imagesize    = 200px\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = G. Evans Essex; Anglo-Australian; Christophus; Coolabah; Drayton; and Kurrajong<ref>\"George Essex Evans.\" [http://www.austlit.edu.au/about'' The Australian Literature Resource''.] 25 September 2008.</ref> \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1863|06|18}}\n| birth_place   = United Kingdom\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1909|11|10|1863|06|18}}\n| death_place   = [[Toowoomba]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n| occupation   = Poet, journalist, farmer, teacher, and public servant<ref>Lee, Chris. \"George Essex Evans.\" [http://www.publicmemory.org/ToowoombaLiteraryHistory/writersEvans.htm Toowoomba's Literary History]. 12 October 2010.</ref>    \n| nationality  = Australian\n| citizenship  = \n| education    = Attended [[Haverfordwest]] Grammar School and James Collegiate School of [[Jersey]]<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\">Tardent, Henry A.(1913)''The Life and Poetry of George Essex Evans: essay written for Brisbane 1913 Eisteddford''. Brisbane: H. Pole.</ref>\n| period       = \n| genre        = Poetry, short stories, journalism, literary criticism, and song lyrics<ref>Arnold, John and John Hay. (2001). \"George Essex Evans.\" ''The Bibliography of Australian Literature''. Vol 1. Victoria: Australian Scholarly Publishing.</ref>   \n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = Blanche Hopkins<ref>Tardent, Henry A.(1913).''The Life and Poetry of George Essex Evans: essay written for Brisbane 1913 Eisteddford''. Brisbane: H. Pole.</ref>  \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n'''George Essex Evans''' (18 June 1863 \u2013 10 November 1909) was an Australian poet.\n\n==Biography==\n\nEvans was born in London on 18 June 1863, to Welsh parents. His father, John Evans Q.C., Treasurer of the [[Inner Temple]] and a member of the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], died in 1864 when his son was only a few months old; he left his family \u00a360,000. George Evans was raised and educated by his mother Mary Ann (n\u00e9e Owen), who was one of the Bowens of Llwynwair, an old Welsh family. She was an educated woman, fluent in both Latin and Greek. The family lived in [[Haverfordwest]] in [[Pembrokeshire]] where Evans attended Haverfordwest Grammar School and then the St. James Collegiate School of [[Jersey]].\n\nEvans was partly deaf and although he was an excellent athlete, his tutors thought him \"dull\". His hearing impediment prevented him going into the armed forces.<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/><ref>Birchley, Delia. (1978). ''The life and works of George Essex Evans (1863-1909)''. Brisbane: University of Queensland.</ref>\n\nIn 1881, when Evans was 17, the siblings J.B.O. (John Bowen Owen), Blanche Gough and Beatrice emigrated to Queensland, Australia, travelling first class on a journey around the Cape of Good Hope that lasted 65 days.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\">Birchley, Delia. (1978). ''The life and works of George Essex Evans (1863-1909).'' Brisbane: University of Queensland.</ref> Upon arrival in Queensland, the brothers bought some land in the [[Darling Downs]] with the intention of farming. Evans, however, was badly injured in a horse riding accident, when he was thrown against a tree, and was unable to do any physical work.<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/> He was able to take part in athletic pursuits, competing in wrestling, running, swimming, and football (in which he represented Queensland).<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n\nEvans suffered from increasing deafness as he grew older, and this may be the reason why he was thought to be a secretive, quiet man.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/> Initially he earned a living by working as a teacher at a private school, but eventually became an Agricultural Editor of ''[[The Queenslander]]''.<ref>\"The Queenslander.\" [http://trove.nla.gov.au/''Australian Newspapers'']. 12 October 2010.</ref> He also wrote travel books for the Government Tourist and Intelligence Bureau.<ref>Lee, Christopher. (2007). \"'From Progress into Stand-still Days': Literature, History and the Darling Downs.\" 'By the Book: a literary history of Queensland.' Eds. Pat Buckridge and Belinda Jane McKay. St Lucia: University of Queensland Press.</ref>  He entered the public service in 1888 and eventually became District Registrar of births, deaths and marriages first for [[Gympie]] and then later for [[Toowoomba]].\n\nIn 1899, Evans married Blanche Hopkins, the young widow of E. B. Hopkins of [[Goondiwindi]], the daughter of the late Rev. William Eglinton and sister of former Native Police Officer, Second-Class Sub-Inspector Ernest Eglinton.<ref>Peters-Little, Frances, Curthoys, Ann and John Docker, eds. (2010) 'Passionate Histories: Myth, Memory and Indigenous Australia.' Acton: Australian National University Press.</ref> The wedding was described as a very secret affair.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/> A letter from Evans to Dr. Black, whom he sought to perform the service, asks for a quiet ceremony with little fuss in Drayton.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/> They were married on 6 November 1899.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n\nEvans and Blanche had two sons. The younger one, Owen Meylett Eglinton Essex Evans, died at five and a half years of ileo colitis acuta (a form of diarrhoea)<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>  As a result of his marriage, Evans also had two stepdaughters, Lorna and Beryl Hopkins.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/><ref>Tardent, Henry A.(1913).''The Life and Poetry of George Essex Evans: essay written for Brisbane 1913 Eisteddford.'' Brisbane: H Pole.</ref>\n\nThey built their home, \"Glenbar\", on the Tollbar Road on the eastern slope of the Toowoomba range. Evans's sister continued to live with him.<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\">{{cite web |url=http://www.toowoombarc.qld.gov.au/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=124&Itemid=115 |title=George Essex Evans - Federation Poet |year=2008 |work=Toowoomba Regional Council |accessdate= 9 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nEvans founded the [[Austral Society]] in [[Toowoomba]] in 1903 to promote music, art, literature, science and industry.<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\"/>\n\nEvans was described as a reserved man, and at times rather moody and impulsive.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Tardent, Henry A.(1913).''The Life and Poetry of George Essex Evans: essay written for Brisbane 1913 Eisteddford.'' Brisbane: H. Pole.</ref> However, he was also described as a kind person and a loyal friend.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> He had a strong sense of honour and self-respect, traits which made him a model husband and father.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nEvans was described as having a tremendous memory, particularly for poetic verse, of which he was able to recite a prodigious amount. Few of his contemporaries were able to match his breadth of knowledge of English, American and Australian poetry.<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/>\n\n==Works==\n\nEvans's works were highly regarded during his career and for a time following his death. He was publicly praised by many acknowledged critics and political figures including [[William Archer (critic)|William Archer]], [[Sir Samuel Griffith]], [[Alfred Deakin]] and [[Sir Henry Parkes]].<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n \nHis first volume of poetry, ''The Repentance of Magdalene Despar'', was published in 1891. Between 1892 and 1897 Evans was associated with [[John Tighe Ryan]] in the production of the periodical ''[[The Antipodean]]'', which appeared three times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/C68399 |title=Austlit - The Antipodean|accessdate= 2 December 2014}}</ref> In 1898 another collection of poetry, ''Loraine and other Verses'', was published. In 1901 Evans won a prize of fifty guineas for his \"Ode for Commonwealth Day\". Although this ode was praised by the then Prime Minister, Alfred Deakin, it was criticised by his peers as trite.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n\n''The Secret Key and other Verses'', which included part of the Loraine volume, was published in 1906. Evans won a reputation in his own state of Queensland as the author of patriotic verse, as in \"Cymru\", and his bush [[ballad]]s, such as \"[[The Women of the West]],\" were popular.\n\nHis work was also noticed by the Queensland State Government. Following the success of ''The Garden of Queensland'', Evans was promoted to the Chief Secretary's department to advertise and \"sell\" Queensland at the Franco-British Exhibition in Paris in May 1908.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n\nEvans also wrote and produced some theatrical works for the Brisbane Theatre including ''[[Robinson Crusoe]]'', a pantomime, and ''Musical Whist''.<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\"/> During the last two years of his life he wrote prolifically about the resources of his state for the Queensland government.\n\nEvans has over 200 published poems attributed to his name. His work frequently appeared in Australian newspapers and he wrote in many other literary forms including short stories, essays, various humorous works and a novella.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austlit.edu.au |title=Austlit Entry George Essex Evans |accessdate= 15 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:GeorgeMemorial.jpg|thumb|alt=George Essex Evans Memorial in Webb Park, Toowoomba|George Essex Evans Memorial in Webb Park, Toowoomba]]\nEvans was a great advocate for the construction of a new road northward across the [[Great Dividing Range|Australia]] and after falling ill in 1909 he became the first passenger to be transported over it when taken to hospital. The men working on the road were so overcome with sorrow for the poet who had worked hard to bring about the new road that they relieved the ambulance men of their duty.<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\"/>\n\nEvans died from complications arising from gallbladder surgery in 1909 at forty-six years of age. The news of his death was first delivered on the stage of the Austral Hall during the largest Austral Festival celebrations ever held. His death prompted an emergency meeting of the Austral Association Committee who, knowing that of all the titles Evans held he was most proud of 'Founder of the Austral Association,' decided that the festival must continue. A series of emotional tributes to his impact on advancing the cause of Australian music, art and literature followed.<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/>\n\nHis funeral was held on 11 November 1909 at the St. James Church<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\"/> and he was eulogized by Alfred Deakin with whom he shared a long correspondence<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adbonline.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080471b.htm |title= Evans, George Essex (1863 - 1909) |last=O'Hagan |first=M.D. |year= 2006 |work=Australian Dictionary of Biography Online Edition |accessdate= 8 October 2010}}</ref> in Federal Parliament as 'Australia's Poet.'<ref name=\"Lee 2009\">{{cite web |url=http://www.publicmemory.org/ToowoombaLiteraryHistory/writersEvans.htm |title=The Literary History of Toowoomba |last=Lee |first=Christopher |year=2009 |work=Public Memory |accessdate= 8 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech that was wired to the poet's widow after his death, Australian Prime Minister Deakin shared his sentiments stating that he was \"Deeply grieved at sudden and unexpected death of your {{sic|hide=y|greatly|-}}gifted husband. Australia will mourn the loss of her national poet whose patriotic songs stirred her people profoundly in the arduous campaign for union.\"<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/>\n\nA memorial of Evans was raised in Webb Park, [[Toowoomba]]. Inscribed on the statue are several verses from his poems, including the following excerpt from his poem \"Toowoomba\":<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usq.edu.au/pmrc/literaryhistory/places/evansmemorial |title=George Essex Evans Memorial |year=2009 |work=University of Southern Queensland |accessdate=12 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414155006/http://www.usq.edu.au/pmrc/literaryhistory/places/evansmemorial |archivedate=14 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n''Dark purple, chased with sudden gloom and glory,''<br />\n''Like waves in wild unrest.''<br />\n''Low-wooded billows and steep summits hoary,''<br />\n''Ridge, slope and mountain crest,''<br />\n''Cease at her feet with faces turned to greet her,''<br />\n''Enthroned, apart, serene,''<br />\n''Above her vassal hills whose voices greet her''<br />\n''The Mountain Queen.''\n\n==Legacy==\n\n[[File:EssexChair.jpg|thumb|alt=Essex Evans' Chair in the Toowoomba City Library.|Essex Evans's chair in the [[Toowoomba]] City Library]]\nAn edition of his ''Collected Verse'' was published in 1928.\n\nAn annual pilgrimage to his memorial site has been carried out by the Toowoomba Ladies Literary Society since 1929. The society have also established a plaque at the site of Essex Evans's home to commemorate his memory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usq.edu.au/pmrc/literaryhistory/history/ladiesliterary |title=The Toowoomba Ladies Literary Society and the Civic Function of a Literary Past |year=2009 |work=University of Southern Queensland |accessdate=8 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311033939/http://www.usq.edu.au/pmrc/literaryhistory/history/ladiesliterary |archivedate=11 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA collection of Essex Evans's artefacts and [[archive]]s can be found at the Toowoomba City Library.<ref name=\"Lee 2009\"/> The Fryer Library at [[The University of Queensland]] also holds his papers.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Poetry collections===\n*''The Repentance of Magdalene Despar and Other Poems'', 1891<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=The repentance of Magdalene Despar : and other poems | publication-date=1891 | publisher=Low, Marston | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/11321072 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''Loraine and other Verses'', 1898<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=Loraine and other verses | publication-date=1898 | publisher=George Robertson & Co | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/17882830 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''The Sword of Pain'', 1905<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=The sword of pain | publication-date=1905 | publisher=Weston & Harrison | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/18653181 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''The Secret Key and Other Verses'', 1906<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | author2=University of Sydney. Library. Scholarly Electronic Text and Image Service | title=The secret key and other verses | publication-date=1998 | publisher=University of Sydney Library, Scholarly Electronic Text and Image Service | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/11322193 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''Kara, and other verses'', 1910<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=Kara and other verses | publication-date=1910 | publisher=Angus and Robertson | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/18993826 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''The Collected Verse of G. Essex Evans'', 1928<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=The collected verse of G. Essex Evans | publication-date=1928 | publisher=Angus and Robertson | edition=Memorial | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/12446757 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Individual poems===\n\n* \"[[The Women of the West]]\" (1901)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Other Reading==\n*''George Essex Evans: Patriotic Poet of Australia - Volume 1 - His Life and Family''. Bill Johnston. Maleny Qld. 2006.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=George Essex Evans |sopt=t}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=10504}}\n* {{cite web|url= http://purl.library.usyd.edu.au/setis/id/v00020 |title=''The Secret Key and Other Verses'' }}\n* ''[http://www.poemhunter.com/i/ebooks/pdf/george_essex_evans_2004_9.pdf Classic Poetry Series: Six Poems by George Essex Evans]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, George Essex}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian poets]]\n[[Category:Australian federationists]]\n[[Category:Darling Downs]]\n[[Category:People from Toowoomba]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> \n| name         = George Essex Evans\n| image        = GeorgeEssexEvans.jpg\n| imagesize    = 200px\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = G. Evans Essex; Anglo-Australian; Christophus; Coolabah; Drayton; and Kurrajong<ref>\"George Essex Evans.\" [http://www.austlit.edu.au/about'' The Australian Literature Resource''.] 25 September 2008.</ref> \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1863|06|18}}\n| birth_place   = United Kingdom\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1909|11|10|1863|06|18}}\n| death_place   = [[Toowoomba]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n| occupation   = Poet, journalist, farmer, teacher, and public servant<ref>Lee, Chris. \"George Essex Evans.\" [http://www.publicmemory.org/ToowoombaLiteraryHistory/writersEvans.htm Toowoomba's Literary History]. 12 October 2010.</ref>    \n| nationality  = Australian\n| citizenship  = \n| education    = Attended [[Haverfordwest]] Grammar School and James Collegiate School of [[Jersey]]<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\">Tardent, Henry A.(1913)''The Life and Poetry of George Essex Evans: essay written for Brisbane 1913 Eisteddford''. Brisbane: H. Pole.</ref>\n| period       = \n| genre        = Poetry, short stories, journalism, literary criticism, and song lyrics<ref>Arnold, John and John Hay. (2001). \"George Essex Evans.\" ''The Bibliography of Australian Literature''. Vol 1. Victoria: Australian Scholarly Publishing.</ref>   \n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = Blanche Hopkins<ref>Tardent, Henry A.(1913).''The Life and Poetry of George Essex Evans: essay written for Brisbane 1913 Eisteddford''. Brisbane: H. Pole.</ref>  \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n'''George Essex Evans''' (18 June 1863 \u2013 10 November 1909) was an Australian poet.\n\n==Biography==\n\nEvans was born in London on 18 June 1863, to Welsh parents. His father, John Evans Q.C., Treasurer of the [[Inner Temple]] and a member of the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], died in 1864 when his son was only a few months old; he left his family \u00a360,000. George Evans was raised and educated by his mother Mary Ann (n\u00e9e Owen), who was one of the Bowens of Llwynwair, an old Welsh family. She was an educated woman, fluent in both Latin and Greek. The family lived in [[Haverfordwest]] in [[Pembrokeshire]] where Evans attended Haverfordwest Grammar School and then the St. James Collegiate School of [[Jersey]].\n\nEvans was partly deaf and although he was an excellent athlete, his tutors thought him \"dull\". His hearing impediment prevented him going into the armed forces.<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/><ref>Birchley, Delia. (1978). ''The life and works of George Essex Evans (1863-1909)''. Brisbane: University of Queensland.</ref>\n\nIn 1881, when Evans was 17, the siblings J.B.O. (John Bowen Owen), Blanche Gough and Beatrice emigrated to Queensland, Australia, travelling first class on a journey around the Cape of Good Hope that lasted 65 days.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\">Birchley, Delia. (1978). ''The life and works of George Essex Evans (1863-1909).'' Brisbane: University of Queensland.</ref> Upon arrival in Queensland, the brothers bought some land in the [[Darling Downs]] with the intention of farming. Evans, however, was badly injured in a horse riding accident, when he was thrown against a tree, and was unable to do any physical work.<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/> He was able to take part in athletic pursuits, competing in wrestling, running, swimming, and football (in which he represented Queensland).<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n\nEvans suffered from increasing deafness as he grew older, and this may be the reason why he was thought to be a secretive, quiet man.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/> Initially he earned a living by working as a teacher at a private school, but eventually became an Agricultural Editor of ''[[The Queenslander]]''.<ref>\"The Queenslander.\" [http://trove.nla.gov.au/''Australian Newspapers'']. 12 October 2010.</ref> He also wrote travel books for the Government Tourist and Intelligence Bureau.<ref>Lee, Christopher. (2007). \"'From Progress into Stand-still Days': Literature, History and the Darling Downs.\" 'By the Book: a literary history of Queensland.' Eds. Pat Buckridge and Belinda Jane McKay. St Lucia: University of Queensland Press.</ref>  He entered the public service in 1888 and eventually became District Registrar of births, deaths and marriages first for [[Gympie]] and then later for [[Toowoomba]].\n\nIn 1899, Evans married Blanche Hopkins, the young widow of E. B. Hopkins of [[Goondiwindi]], the daughter of the late Rev. William Eglinton and sister of former Native Police Officer, Second-Class Sub-Inspector Ernest Eglinton.<ref>Peters-Little, Frances, Curthoys, Ann and John Docker, eds. (2010) 'Passionate Histories: Myth, Memory and Indigenous Australia.' Acton: Australian National University Press.</ref> The wedding was described as a very secret affair.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/> A letter from Evans to Dr. Black, whom he sought to perform the service, asks for a quiet ceremony with little fuss in Drayton.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/> They were married on 6 November 1899.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n\nEvans and Blanche had two sons. The younger one, Owen Meylett Eglinton Essex Evans, died at five and a half years of ileo colitis acuta (a form of diarrhoea)<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>  As a result of his marriage, Evans also had two stepdaughters, Lorna and Beryl Hopkins.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/><ref>Tardent, Henry A.(1913).''The Life and Poetry of George Essex Evans: essay written for Brisbane 1913 Eisteddford.'' Brisbane: H Pole.</ref>\n\nThey built their home, \"Glenbar\", on the Tollbar Road on the eastern slope of the Toowoomba range. Evans's sister continued to live with him.<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\">{{cite web |url=http://www.toowoombarc.qld.gov.au/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=124&Itemid=115 |title=George Essex Evans - Federation Poet |year=2008 |work=Toowoomba Regional Council |accessdate= 9 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nEvans founded the [[Austral Society]] in [[Toowoomba]] in 1903 to promote music, art, literature, science and industry.<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\"/>\n\nEvans was described as a reserved man, and at times rather moody and impulsive.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Tardent, Henry A.(1913).''The Life and Poetry of George Essex Evans: essay written for Brisbane 1913 Eisteddford.'' Brisbane: H. Pole.</ref> However, he was also described as a kind person and a loyal friend.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> He had a strong sense of honour and self-respect, traits which made him a model husband and father.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nEvans was described as having a tremendous memory, particularly for poetic verse, of which he was able to recite a prodigious amount. Few of his contemporaries were able to match his breadth of knowledge of English, American and Australian poetry.<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/>\n\n==Works==\n\nEvans's works were highly regarded during his career and for a time following his death. He was publicly praised by many acknowledged critics and political figures including [[William Archer (critic)|William Archer]], [[Sir Samuel Griffith]], [[Alfred Deakin]] and [[Sir Henry Parkes]].<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n \nHis first volume of poetry, ''The Repentance of Magdalene Despar'', was published in 1891. Between 1892 and 1897 Evans was associated with [[John Tighe Ryan]] in the production of the periodical ''[[The Antipodean]]'', which appeared three times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/C68399 |title=Austlit - The Antipodean|accessdate= 2 December 2014}}</ref> In 1898 another collection of poetry, ''Loraine and other Verses'', was published. In 1901 Evans won a prize of fifty guineas for his \"Ode for Commonwealth Day\". Although this ode was praised by the then Prime Minister, Alfred Deakin, it was criticised by his peers as trite.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n\n''The Secret Key and other Verses'', which included part of the Loraine volume, was published in 1906. Evans won a reputation in his own state of Queensland as the author of patriotic verse, as in \"Cymru\", and his bush [[ballad]]s, such as \"[[The Women of the West]],\" were popular.\n\nHis work was also noticed by the Queensland State Government. Following the success of ''The Garden of Queensland'', Evans was promoted to the Chief Secretary's department to advertise and \"sell\" Queensland at the Franco-British Exhibition in Paris in May 1908.<ref name=\"Birchley, Delia 1978\"/>\n\nEvans also wrote and produced some theatrical works for the Brisbane Theatre including ''[[Robinson Crusoe]]'', a pantomime, and ''Musical Whist''.<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\"/> During the last two years of his life he wrote prolifically about the resources of his state for the Queensland government.\n\nEvans has over 200 published poems attributed to his name. His work frequently appeared in Australian newspapers and he wrote in many other literary forms including short stories, essays, various humorous works and a novella.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austlit.edu.au |title=Austlit Entry George Essex Evans |accessdate= 15 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:GeorgeMemorial.jpg|thumb|alt=George Essex Evans Memorial in Webb Park, Toowoomba|George Essex Evans Memorial in Webb Park, Toowoomba]]\nEvans was a great advocate for the construction of a new road northward across the [[Great Dividing Range|Australia]] and after falling ill in 1909 he became the first passenger to be transported over it when taken to hospital. The men working on the road were so overcome with sorrow for the poet who had worked hard to bring about the new road that they relieved the ambulance men of their duty.<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\"/>\n\nEvans died from complications arising from gallbladder surgery in 1909 at forty-six years of age. The news of his death was first delivered on the stage of the Austral Hall during the largest Austral Festival celebrations ever held. His death prompted an emergency meeting of the Austral Association Committee who, knowing that of all the titles Evans held he was most proud of 'Founder of the Austral Association,' decided that the festival must continue. A series of emotional tributes to his impact on advancing the cause of Australian music, art and literature followed.<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/>\n\nHis funeral was held on 11 November 1909 at the St. James Church<ref name=\"toowoombarc.qld.gov.au\"/> and he was eulogized by Alfred Deakin with whom he shared a long correspondence<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adbonline.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080471b.htm |title= Evans, George Essex (1863 - 1909) |last=O'Hagan |first=M.D. |year= 2006 |work=Australian Dictionary of Biography Online Edition |accessdate= 8 October 2010}}</ref> in Federal Parliament as 'Australia's Poet.'<ref name=\"Lee 2009\">{{cite web |url=http://www.publicmemory.org/ToowoombaLiteraryHistory/writersEvans.htm |title=The Literary History of Toowoomba |last=Lee |first=Christopher |year=2009 |work=Public Memory |accessdate= 8 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech that was wired to the poet's widow after his death, Australian Prime Minister Deakin shared his sentiments stating that he was \"Deeply grieved at sudden and unexpected death of your {{sic|hide=y|greatly|-}}gifted husband. Australia will mourn the loss of her national poet whose patriotic songs stirred her people profoundly in the arduous campaign for union.\"<ref name=\"Tardent, Henry A. 1913\"/>\n\nA memorial of Evans was raised in Webb Park, [[Toowoomba]]. Inscribed on the statue are several verses from his poems, including the following excerpt from his poem \"Toowoomba\":<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usq.edu.au/pmrc/literaryhistory/places/evansmemorial |title=George Essex Evans Memorial |year=2009 |work=University of Southern Queensland |accessdate=12 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414155006/http://www.usq.edu.au/pmrc/literaryhistory/places/evansmemorial |archivedate=14 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n''Dark purple, chased with sudden gloom and glory,''<br />\n''Like waves in wild unrest.''<br />\n''Low-wooded billows and steep summits hoary,''<br />\n''Ridge, slope and mountain crest,''<br />\n''Cease at her feet with faces turned to greet her,''<br />\n''Enthroned, apart, serene,''<br />\n''Above her vassal hills whose voices greet her''<br />\n''The Mountain Queen.''\n\n==Legacy==\n\n[[File:EssexChair.jpg|thumb|alt=Essex Evans' Chair in the Toowoomba City Library.|Essex Evans's chair in the [[Toowoomba]] City Library]]\nAn edition of his ''Collected Verse'' was published in 1928.\n\nAn annual pilgrimage to his memorial site has been carried out by the Toowoomba Ladies Literary Society since 1929. The society have also established a plaque at the site of Essex Evans's home to commemorate his memory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usq.edu.au/pmrc/literaryhistory/history/ladiesliterary |title=The Toowoomba Ladies Literary Society and the Civic Function of a Literary Past |year=2009 |work=University of Southern Queensland |accessdate=8 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311033939/http://www.usq.edu.au/pmrc/literaryhistory/history/ladiesliterary |archivedate=11 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA collection of Essex Evans's artefacts and [[archive]]s can be found at the Toowoomba City Library.<ref name=\"Lee 2009\"/> The Fryer Library at [[The University of Queensland]] also holds his papers.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Poetry collections===\n*''The Repentance of Magdalene Despar and Other Poems'', 1891<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=The repentance of Magdalene Despar : and other poems | publication-date=1891 | publisher=Low, Marston | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/11321072 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''Loraine and other Verses'', 1898<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=Loraine an other verses | publication-date=1898 | publisher=George Robertson & Co | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/17882830 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''The Sword of Pain'', 1905<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=The sword of pain | publication-date=1905 | publisher=Weston & Harrison | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/18653181 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''The Secret Key and Other Verses'', 1906<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | author2=University of Sydney. Library. Scholarly Electronic Text and Image Service | title=The secret key and other verses | publication-date=1998 | publisher=University of Sydney Library, Scholarly Electronic Text and Image Service | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/11322193 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''Kara, and other verses'', 1910<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=Kara and other verses | publication-date=1910 | publisher=Angus and Robertson | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/18993826 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n*''The Collected Verse of G. Essex Evans'', 1928<ref>{{Citation | author1=Evans, George Essex | title=The collected verse of G. Essex Evans | publication-date=1928 | publisher=Angus and Robertson | edition=Memorial | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/12446757 | accessdate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Individual poems===\n\n* \"[[The Women of the West]]\" (1901)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Other Reading==\n*''George Essex Evans: Patriotic Poet of Australia - Volume 1 - His Life and Family''. Bill Johnston. Maleny Qld. 2006.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=George Essex Evans |sopt=t}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=10504}}\n* {{cite web|url= http://purl.library.usyd.edu.au/setis/id/v00020 |title=''The Secret Key and Other Verses'' }}\n* ''[http://www.poemhunter.com/i/ebooks/pdf/george_essex_evans_2004_9.pdf Classic Poetry Series: Six Poems by George Essex Evans]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, George Essex}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian poets]]\n[[Category:Australian federationists]]\n[[Category:Darling Downs]]\n[[Category:People from Toowoomba]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian poets]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePoetry collections:Typo fixing, replaced: an other  \u2192  another", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Essex_Evans"}
